## Architecture Review — 2026-03-16

### Codebase Health: On Track

The codebase is in excellent shape. `cargo check`, `cargo clippy -D warnings`, and all 891 tests pass clean. The workspace-wide lint set (`unwrap_used = "deny"`, `unsafe_code = "forbid"`, `todo = "deny"`) is enforced and the code complies.

### Security Posture: Strong

All critical properties verified and clean:
- AES-256-CTR with monotonically advancing `ctr_block_offset` per agent — no CTR reuse possible
- `Zeroizing<Vec<u8>>` on all key material
- Argon2id + dummy verifier for user enumeration prevention
- `subtle::ConstantTimeEq` for token comparisons
- HMAC-SHA256 API keys with per-IP rate limiting
- Webhook SSRF prevention (`redirect::Policy::none()`)
- RBAC enforced as Axum extractors
- DNS sessions bound to source IP

**No open security findings.**

### Issues Filed

| ID | Priority | Agent | Description |
|----|----------|-------|-------------|
| `red-cell-c2-dhhb` | P4 | Codex | `dispatch/mod.rs:1352` — `i64::try_from(len).unwrap_or_default()` silently records `size_bytes=0` for credential content ≥ 2^63 bytes |
| `red-cell-c2-wuqv` | P4 | Codex | `dispatch/filesystem.rs` + `transfer.rs` — `u64::try_from(data.len()).unwrap_or_default()` emits false 0-progress events on overflow (dead code on 64-bit but semantically wrong) |

Both attributed to Codex commit `a849a947` (feat: capture agent loot and credentials).

### Biggest Blindspot

The `unwrap_or_default()` pattern on integer narrowing conversions is a recurring minor code quality issue — it consistently produces semantically wrong fallbacks (0) instead of signalling overflow. Four production sites identified. No security impact on 64-bit targets but worth a focused cleanup pass.

### Agent Quality

| Agent | Tasks | Bugs | Quality |
|-------|-------|------|---------|
| Claude | 181 | 33 | 82% |
| Codex | 181 | 30 | 83% |
| Cursor | 31 | 9 | 71% |

Codex leads marginally but all three are within expected range. Both findings this run are low-severity cosmetic correctness issues — the serious categories (security, protocol, panics) are now well-controlled.

### Recommendation

1. Fix `red-cell-c2-wuqv`: replace the four `try_from(len).unwrap_or_default()` calls with `len as u64` (safe on all supported 64-bit targets)
2. Audit for any other `try_from(usize).unwrap_or_default()` patterns across the codebase
